This is a textbook case of **coverage-gaming**. Every production method is called (→ 95% line coverage), but almost nothing is actually verified. Here's the severity-ranked audit:

---

## 🔴 CRITICAL — Assert-Free Tests (fire-and-forget)

These tests have **zero assertions**. They'll pass even if the production code is completely wrong.

### 1. `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)
Calls `AddProduct` but never verifies the product was stored.
```csharp
// FIX:
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var retrieved = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(retrieved);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", retrieved.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, retrieved.Price);
```

### 2. `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)
Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the price actually changed.
```csharp
// FIX:
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

### 3. `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 38)
Calls `RemoveProduct` but never verifies the product is gone.
```csharp
// FIX:
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

### 4. `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)
Calls `GetProductCount` on an **empty** catalog, captures no result, asserts nothing.
```csharp
// FIX:
Assert.AreEqual(0, _catalog.GetProductCount());
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
Assert.AreEqual(1, _catalog.GetProductCount());
```

### 5. `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 68)
Applies a 10% discount but never checks that prices were reduced.
```csharp
// FIX:
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
```

### 6. `ImportFromCsv_Works` (line 84)
Imports CSV but never checks the product was created.
